# RadMo .clinerules

## Project Intelligence & Patterns

### Communication Style

**Tone Model:** Tim Urban (Waitbutwhy)
- Accessible and humorous without being reductive
- Pattern-recognizing over moralistic
- Challenge elitism, preach-iness; accessibility is non-negotiable
- Use specific examples over abstract frameworks (though named concepts are strong)

**Artifact Quality:** Production-grade UI
- Prefer elegant, refined design over quickly-built mockups
- Use Tailwind CSS core utilities (no custom compilers)
- Multi-dimensional visualizations (radar/spider charts > bar charts)
- Responsive design mindset even in prototype phase

**Documentation:** Concrete > abstract
- Named frameworks over prose (Silence Tax > "the quiet majority problem")
- Code comments should explain *why*, not *what*
- Decision logs capture tradeoffs and constraints
- Avoid long essays; prefer bullet-point specs

### Developer Preferences

**Collaboration Style:**
- Sean drives strategy; Claude is collaborative builder across all phases (vision → design → code)
- Expect challenge and pushback on elitism or accessibility failures
- Strong opinions on incentive design; not arbitrary on this
- Rapid iteration through artifacts; feedback loops are tight

**Code Organization:**
- React components live in artifacts for rapid feedback
- GitHub commits bundle conceptually-related changes
- Stub commits + full commits pattern (prototype → finalize)
- JSX files should be readable in one scroll (keep <200 lines)

**Research Approach:**
- Deep-dive references (Community Notes source, sentiment analysis models) happen in focused sessions
- Always cite the actual source (github.com/twitter/communitynotes) not summarized versions
- Validate hypotheses with examples from competitive landscape (Ground News, Reddit, X)

### Technical Patterns

**Credibility Score Design:**
- Always 30/30/25/15 weighting unless explicitly changed (is/ought, cross-viewpoint, source diversity, consistency)
- Visualization should make weighting transparent to users
- Radar charts preferred for multi-dimensional display (clearer hierarchy than bars)

**Is/Ought Separation:**
- Letter-by-letter gradient approach: green (is) → yellow (mixed) → red (ought)
- Currently visual design; next phase is algorithmic operationalization
- This is a measurable, differentiating feature—not abstract philosophy

**Cooling Period:**
- 24-72 hour configurable delay before reactions visible
- Deliberately less addictive; friction is a feature
- UX must make users aware of delay without creating friction

**Behavioral Credibility:**
- Account legitimacy + consistency + cross-viewpoint engagement + prediction accuracy
- Reddit bot-checking behavior shows users want this; make it transparent
- Avoid gaming via multi-signal approach; single metrics are exploitable

### Design Decisions (Do Not Reverse)

**Binary Left-Right Model:** RadMo intentionally goes beyond it
- Community Notes proved binary bridging works
- RadMo's evolution to multi-dimensional/cross-cultural is genuine product advantage
- Do not regress to simpler binary model

**Original Content Over Aggregation:**
- Moderation burden accepted as tradeoff
- Differentiation requires community-generated content
- This is a deliberate choice, not a constraint

**Incentive Alignment Over Morality:**
- Platform succeeds by making epistemic quality the path of least resistance
- Do not frame features as "be a better person"
- Reframe as status-seeking, dopamine substitutes, intellectual rebellion

**Transparency as Differentiation:**
- Explicit business model (subscription, no engagement-driven ads) is a trust signal
- Do not hide monetization strategy
- Make it part of the value proposition

### Open Questions & Constraints

**Highest Risk:** Dopamine gap
- Why stay on RadMo if cooling period removes reward loop?
- Credibility status + insight velocity are hypothesized substitutes
- Must validate before MVP; may require user testing

**Design Unresolved:** "Someone Like You / Someone Unlike You" popup
- Four open questions: signals, trigger timing, opt-in vs. proactive, interaction depth
- This feature touches core value prop; design decision is critical

**Validation Needed:**
- Behavioral credibility signal weighting (how much account age vs. consistency?)
- Prediction market monetary design (how to balance accuracy vs. participation?)
- Content moderation strategy (human + algorithmic hybrid?)

### Red Flags / What Not to Do

- ❌ Don't reduce credibility to a single metric (exploitable)
- ❌ Don't frame features moralistically ("be open-minded"; instead "status + insight")
- ❌ Don't return to binary left-right framing (Community Notes' known weakness)
- ❌ Don't prioritize time-on-app over time-to-insight
- ❌ Don't let "better information environment" stay abstract (operationalize it)

### Tools & Workflow

**GitHub MCP:** Available on Windows desktop
- Fine-grained PAT (Contents read/write, Metadata read-only)
- Use for commits, branch management, source code review
- Check structure regularly; keep organized

**React Artifacts:** Primary prototyping tool
- Rapid iteration → stakeholder feedback → finalization
- Commit full versions (not stubs) to repo
- Use Tailwind core utilities; prefer semantic HTML

**Research Sessions:** Focused deep-dives
- Community Notes algorithm study → architecture implications
- Sentiment analysis tool evaluation → bias detection approach
- Prediction market design → monetary incentive structure

**Memory Bank Updates:** After significant decisions or design changes
- Update activeContext.md and progress.md frequently
- Update systemPatterns.md when patterns change
- Review all files monthly for consistency

